@ThinkingandTinkering I lived in Canada (1976-86) and did a lot of back and forth between Calgary, Alta and Vancouver, BC. The elevation difference made for some new and weird observations. E.g. it felt colder in BC at -5 to +5 than it did in Alta at -20/-40 (three layers and a good breakfast and you were fine). Humidity goes through clothes, everywhere, magnifying the effect of temperature.
Back in Australia my girlfriends learned to love me even more when I soaked the top sheet and threw it over them (with the obligatory squeal): but that was back in the day when we had real heat waves.
Thanks for reminding me.
